On the shoulder of the vase are two tubular handles, both covered by rectangular gold plates with an openwork cross cut in the middle. The base was drilled right through for ease of hollowing, and would have been plugged by a separate piece of stone, now missing.

description.value: Pottery: coarse ware basket vase.  A double-faced pot, oval in cross-section, with a basket-handle: on one side is the face of a maenad, with a frowning brow and prominent lines bracketing her dimpled chin; she has curls on top of her head and vertical locks falling to her brow and framing her face. The other side has the face of a young satyr with a closely woven wreath adorned with ivy berries crossing above his forehead, his hair showing above and falling beside his face. The resting-surface of the pot is slightly concave.  Two-piece mould, with applied handle above. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt, with the remains of a white dressing outside and in, but not under the base; a little black paint survives on the eyes, and the face of the maenad is painted pink; the hair of the satyr has red paint, and pink paint was used on his wreath.

description.value: Pottery vase: this vase is shaped like a woman carrying a small child on her back. On her lap she holds a simple horn container, with the spoon resting on her open left palm. The child is wrapped in his mother's shawl, the fringed edge of which is visible along his back. His legs can be seen beneath the shawl; with his free right arm, he clutches his mother's upper arm. The crossing edges of the mother's garments are difficult to interpret, but beneath the shawl there is at least one garment, tied at the neck. The woman wears her hair in a long ponytail which partially covers the child's body. She has two strands of beads around her neck; the child seems to wear a single bracelet. The figure's pose is well balanced and relaxed. The spout is completely separate from the handle, which is a ring attached to the back of the head.
